The paper deals with computational mechanism design, which is a subfield of theoretical computer science that studies the design of algorithms and protocols for strategic agents. The problem studied in the paper is a classic problem in mechanism design, namely selling heterogeneous items to unit-demand bidders. This problem falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT) and algorithmic mechanism design (cs.EC). The paper also uses techniques from computational geometry and algebra, which suggests that it could be relevant to the sub-categories of computational geometry (cs.CG) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper deals with randomized mechanisms and their computational tractability, which could make it relevant to the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and information theory (cs.IT).
